00:28:09.104 --> 00:28:11.744
said as much. I think there are people who

501
00:28:11.744 --> 00:28:14.305
have too dark a view, who are too pessimistic,

502
00:28:14.415 --> 00:28:17.905
who are depressed out of proportion to reality. In

503
00:28:17.905 --> 00:28:21.375
other words, they're more depressed than reality should render

504
00:28:21.375 --> 00:28:23.540
them. Uh, BUT I just don't think that's the

505
00:28:23.540 --> 00:28:27.280
dominant view. The psychological evidence suggests that most people

506
00:28:27.619 --> 00:28:30.619
are susceptible to an optimism bias, but that's not

507
00:28:30.619 --> 00:28:33.349
to say that there are not many people who

508
00:28:33.540 --> 00:28:36.089
have the opposite bias. They've got too pessimistic a

509
00:28:36.089 --> 00:28:36.339
view.

510
00:28:37.520 --> 00:28:42.130
So you think that and now talking from an

511
00:28:42.130 --> 00:28:47.770
objective perspective that in human life there is more

512
00:28:47.770 --> 00:28:49.530
bad than good.

513
00:28:51.479 --> 00:28:53.640
I do think so. The claim you've just made

514
00:28:53.640 --> 00:28:57.300
is ambiguous between human life as a whole and

515
00:28:57.300 --> 00:28:59.319
any individual human life, but I do think that

516
00:28:59.319 --> 00:29:02.020
it's true on both of those interpretations.

517
00:29:02.869 --> 00:29:06.619
Mhm. So, uh, let me ask you now about,

518
00:29:06.689 --> 00:29:10.599
uh, what in the book you call secular theodicies

519
00:29:10.599 --> 00:29:17.089
or particularly secular optimistic theodesis. Like for example, saying

520
00:29:17.089 --> 00:29:22.670
that bad things in life are necessary or more

521
00:29:22.670 --> 00:29:28.150
specifically that bad things in life are necessary in

522
00:29:28.150 --> 00:29:32.709
order to appreciate the good things. I mean, do

523
00:29:32.709 --> 00:29:37.310
you think that bad things are really necessary in

524
00:29:37.310 --> 00:29:42.430
life for for for those kinds of purposes that

525
00:29:42.430 --> 00:29:44.430
people refer to?

526
00:29:46.380 --> 00:29:48.140
Well, I think there's an ambiguity there in the

527
00:29:48.140 --> 00:29:50.459
necessity. So one question you could be making is,

528
00:29:50.579 --> 00:29:54.060
given the psychological construct of people, they're not going

529
00:29:54.060 --> 00:29:56.780
to appreciate the good things unless they have the

530
00:29:56.780 --> 00:30:00.459
bad things. But another interpretation is to say, could

531
00:30:00.459 --> 00:30:02.780
there be a kind of being that was not

532
00:30:02.780 --> 00:30:05.819
so psychologically constituted? In other words, a kind of

533
00:30:05.819 --> 00:30:08.859
being who could appreciate the good things, uh, without

534
00:30:08.859 --> 00:30:13.050
experiencing the bad things. So, those are two interpretations

535
00:30:13.050 --> 00:30:16.439
of the necessity condition. That you've mentioned. And I

536
00:30:16.439 --> 00:30:22.010
wanna say, really on I, it, it, it, if,

537
00:30:22.089 --> 00:30:26.770
if you require suffering in order to experience, really

538
00:30:26.770 --> 00:30:29.010
experience the good, it would have been better if

539
00:30:29.010 --> 00:30:30.859
you'd not been that kind of being. And so,

540
00:30:31.079 --> 00:30:33.050
this is a worse kind of existence than a

541
00:30:33.050 --> 00:30:35.130
kind of existence where you don't need to have

542
00:30:35.369 --> 00:30:37.290
the bad things in order to experience the good

543
00:30:37.290 --> 00:30:40.400
things. I also wonder, even on its own terms,

544
00:30:40.449 --> 00:30:42.770
whether we need to have quite as much suffering

545
00:30:42.770 --> 00:30:45.050
in the world in order to produce the good

546
00:30:45.050 --> 00:30:47.209
things. It seems sort of a little perverse if

547
00:30:47.209 --> 00:30:51.339
you've got to have Mass starvation and poverty and

548
00:30:51.719 --> 00:30:54.719
millions of people dying of cancer and people taking

549
00:30:54.719 --> 00:30:56.760
their own lives because they're so depressed that you've

550
00:30:56.760 --> 00:30:59.310
gotta have all of that evil in order for

551
00:30:59.310 --> 00:31:04.540
you to be deriving satisfaction from your first, uh,

552
00:31:05.119 --> 00:31:06.380
helping of dessert.

553
00:31:07.839 --> 00:31:14.189
Right, right. What about the secular theodicy that claims

554
00:31:14.189 --> 00:31:18.430
that there are constraints on how good a human

555
00:31:18.430 --> 00:31:23.489
life can be while still being a human life?

556
00:31:24.989 --> 00:31:28.630
I think that that fetishizes the importance of a

557
00:31:28.630 --> 00:31:32.229
life being a human life. So, let's think, let's

558
00:31:32.229 --> 00:31:35.630
say about longevity. We, we live much longer than

559
00:31:35.630 --> 00:31:41.239
mice do, even in, in the wild. And A

560
00:31:41.239 --> 00:31:44.359
mouse's lifespan is really rather short. It's a year

561
00:31:44.359 --> 00:31:48.719
or two, as I recall. MAYBE slightly mistaken about

562
00:31:48.719 --> 00:31:51.199
that, but it's something like 1 year or 2.

563
00:31:51.729 --> 00:31:55.329
And you can imagine a kind of Murian philosopher

564
00:31:55.329 --> 00:31:58.209
saying, well, you shouldn't really be judging the quality

565
00:31:58.209 --> 00:32:02.489
of mice, mice, mice's lives by human standards. You

566
00:32:02.489 --> 00:32:04.589
shouldn't be pointing to those humans that live for

567
00:32:04.680 --> 00:32:07.650
70, 80, 90 years and saying, look how bad

568
00:32:07.650 --> 00:32:09.449
it is uh to be a mouse because we

569
00:32:09.449 --> 00:32:13.099
wouldn't be mice if we lived much longer. Now,

570
00:32:13.219 --> 00:32:15.619
of course, there's one question about whether we, whether

571
00:32:15.619 --> 00:32:18.060
they really wouldn't be mice because if they had

572
00:32:18.060 --> 00:32:20.530
all the other features of being mice, but somehow

573
00:32:20.530 --> 00:32:22.979
they could live for much longer, my money would

574
00:32:22.979 --> 00:32:26.920
be that they are still mice. But even if

575
00:32:27.739 --> 00:32:31.300
that alteration in lifespan meant some kind of alteration

576
00:32:31.300 --> 00:32:34.699
in the species, but these beings actually lived longer

577
00:32:34.699 --> 00:32:37.689
and better lives, I would say it's much better

578
00:32:37.689 --> 00:32:41.040
to be a trance mouse than a mouse. And

579
00:32:41.040 --> 00:32:43.489
I would say something similar about a human being,

580
00:32:43.880 --> 00:32:48.359
that if extending our lifespan while not increasing the

581
00:32:48.359 --> 00:32:50.150
amount of evil within one's life, you know, there's,

582
00:32:50.160 --> 00:32:52.400
the amount of harm in one's life, if you

583
00:32:52.400 --> 00:32:54.000
could do that, if you could go on for

584
00:32:54.000 --> 00:32:57.239
youthful vigor for 500 years rather than youthful vigor

585
00:32:57.239 --> 00:32:59.680
just for 10 or 12 years, then I think

586
00:32:59.680 --> 00:33:01.640
that would be a better thing even if we

587
00:33:01.640 --> 00:33:03.939
cease to be distinctly human.

588
00:33:05.510 --> 00:33:10.729
So do you have an opinion on transhumanism and

589
00:33:11.550 --> 00:33:16.709
the suggestion that perhaps we could try as best

590
00:33:16.709 --> 00:33:21.550
as we can to eliminate suffering from human life?

591
00:33:21.660 --> 00:33:25.890
Do you think that if we could achieve such

592
00:33:25.890 --> 00:33:30.949
a goal, it would contribute to the betterment of

593
00:33:30.949 --> 00:33:33.150
our human predicament?

594
00:33:35.410 --> 00:33:37.030
I think it would be better if we could

595
00:33:37.030 --> 00:33:40.540
reduce suffering in either human lives or if human

596
00:33:40.540 --> 00:33:43.510
lives were to alter into some kind of transhuman

597
00:33:43.510 --> 00:33:47.170
or posthuman life. But I do think that these

598
00:33:47.170 --> 00:33:52.319
pictures are very often another form of secular theodicy,

599
00:33:52.660 --> 00:33:56.660
secular optimistic theodicy, because I strongly suspect that they

600
00:33:56.660 --> 00:34:00.910
are. Excessively optimistic in what they think can be

601
00:34:00.910 --> 00:34:01.410
achieved.

602
00:34:03.310 --> 00:34:06.459
And uh you know, no, go ahead, go ahead,

603
00:34:06.589 --> 00:34:06.969
sorry.

604
00:34:08.030 --> 00:34:10.770
Uh, THE reason why I think that is because

605
00:34:11.110 --> 00:34:13.550
if you prevent some kind of problems, I think

606
00:34:13.550 --> 00:34:15.188
new problems are very likely to come in their

607
00:34:15.188 --> 00:34:18.168
wake. So, if you think about the great success

608
00:34:18.550 --> 00:34:21.810
that the developed world had for a while in

609
00:34:22.030 --> 00:34:25.668
curtailing infectious diseases, so people weren't dying, let's say,

610
00:34:25.708 --> 00:34:29.469
in infancy from infectious diseases or in in young

611
00:34:29.469 --> 00:34:32.070
adulthood, but then they started dying of other things,

612
00:34:32.228 --> 00:34:35.449
cancer and degenerative diseases, and If we manage to

613
00:34:35.449 --> 00:34:37.449
cure those, then I think we'll find that people

614
00:34:37.449 --> 00:34:42.250
start dying of something else. Because mortality and decay

615
00:34:42.250 --> 00:34:46.320
and degeneration, these are all just parts of the

616
00:34:46.530 --> 00:34:50.228
physical world, and I, I think that Many of

617
00:34:50.228 --> 00:34:52.750
these people have just too optimistic a view about

618
00:34:52.750 --> 00:34:54.790
how much that can be eradicated.

619
00:34:56.540 --> 00:35:01.600
So do you think that I mean, even if

620
00:35:01.600 --> 00:35:08.030
we could eliminate as much suffering as possible from

621
00:35:08.030 --> 00:35:15.179
human life, even that wouldn't make it worth starting,

622
00:35:15.239 --> 00:35:21.340
that it wouldn't make it worth creating new humans.

623
00:35:22.560 --> 00:35:24.280
That I think is true because I think that

624
00:35:24.280 --> 00:35:27.000
there would still be considerable suffering and so it

625
00:35:27.000 --> 00:35:29.280
would never be in somebody, never actually be in

626
00:35:29.280 --> 00:35:32.320
somebody's interest to be brought into existence. But that's

627
00:35:32.320 --> 00:35:34.040
not to say that I'm opposed to our doing

628
00:35:34.040 --> 00:35:36.679
what we can do to make lives better, because

629
00:35:36.679 --> 00:35:39.550
that's certainly going to have value for existing people.

630
00:35:40.159 --> 00:35:43.520
Uh, I would question though, the kind of utopian

631
00:35:43.520 --> 00:35:45.719
pictures that are often presented to us. I just

632
00:35:45.719 --> 00:35:48.919
think that they are very unlikely to be true.

633
00:35:49.330 --> 00:35:51.330
The, the future will tell whether I'm right or

634
00:35:51.330 --> 00:35:53.649
whether they're right. I, I'm not denying for the

635
00:35:53.649 --> 00:35:57.350
record that some improvements can't take place. I just

636
00:35:57.810 --> 00:36:01.169
doubt that death can be eradicated, that disease can

637
00:36:01.169 --> 00:36:04.689
be eradicated. These are very ambitious projects that I

638
00:36:04.689 --> 00:36:06.909
think are unlikely to be deliverable.

639
00:36:08.449 --> 00:36:12.330
So, uh, let's talk a little bit about death

640
00:36:12.330 --> 00:36:16.729
because of course it's one of the aspects of

641
00:36:16.729 --> 00:36:20.489
our lives that is, uh, I think, or at

642
00:36:20.489 --> 00:36:24.239
least for the time being unless there's a future,

643
00:36:24.330 --> 00:36:28.389
uh there's a future, I don't know exactly when

644
00:36:28.389 --> 00:36:31.409
where we will, we will not have to deal

645
00:36:31.409 --> 00:36:36.330
with death anymore, but uh why does death matter

646
00:36:36.330 --> 00:36:37.929
for our predicament?

647
00:36:39.050 --> 00:36:41.639
Well, on my view, uh, death is bad. In

648
00:36:41.639 --> 00:36:43.709
other words, life is bad, but so is death.

649
00:36:44.129 --> 00:36:48.020
And that's one of the features that creates the

650
00:36:48.020 --> 00:36:50.110
human predicament. It's either the rock or the hard

651
00:36:50.110 --> 00:36:53.870
place. Now, of course, not all philosophers have this

652
00:36:53.870 --> 00:36:57.110
view, and there's an ancient philosophical tradition, the Epicurean

653
00:36:57.110 --> 00:37:00.189
tradition, which just denies that death is bad for

654
00:37:00.189 --> 00:37:02.750
the, for the being who dies. And if that

655
00:37:02.750 --> 00:37:08.080
view is correct, well, then it's The predicament is

656
00:37:08.080 --> 00:37:10.719
not of the kind that I'm suggesting. It may

657
00:37:10.719 --> 00:37:12.560
be still that it's hard for people to take

658
00:37:12.560 --> 00:37:15.360
their own lives, but there would be, in a

659
00:37:15.360 --> 00:37:19.169
sense, a cost-free exit. But I think that that

660
00:37:19.169 --> 00:37:22.649
epicurean view is mistaken, not in a provable way.

661
00:37:22.719 --> 00:37:25.489
It's not that I can give you. What's called

662
00:37:25.489 --> 00:37:28.290
a knockdown argument to show that the Epicureans are

663
00:37:28.290 --> 00:37:31.090
wrong, but I think on a balance of considerations,

664
00:37:31.129 --> 00:37:34.169
which I do examine in the book, we should

665
00:37:34.169 --> 00:37:36.929
reach the conclusion that death is bad and that

666
00:37:36.929 --> 00:37:39.689
it's a pretty serious bad. That's not to say

667
00:37:39.689 --> 00:37:42.370
that death is, is always the worst thing that

668
00:37:42.370 --> 00:37:44.280
can happen to you. There are fates that are

669
00:37:44.280 --> 00:37:47.350
worse than death. And I think that sometimes death

670
00:37:47.969 --> 00:37:50.120
is going to be the lesser of two evils,

671
00:37:50.530 --> 00:37:53.570
but it always comes at serious cost to the

672
00:37:53.570 --> 00:37:57.189
being who dies, even if that cost is sometimes

673
00:37:57.449 --> 00:38:00.250
less than the cost of remaining alive.

674
00:38:01.270 --> 00:38:06.530
But assuming that there's no afterlife, there's no life

675
00:38:06.530 --> 00:38:10.010
after death, um, and I think there's of course

676
00:38:10.010 --> 00:38:14.090
very good reasons to assume that. Do you think

677
00:38:14.090 --> 00:38:20.320
that uh death would be bad just as the

678
00:38:20.330 --> 00:38:25.229
process itself, there is the the moment you go

679
00:38:25.929 --> 00:38:30.010
through death, that would be the bad thing about

680
00:38:30.010 --> 00:38:35.419
it. And then what comes after, since there's nothing

681
00:38:35.419 --> 00:38:39.770
to experience, no suffering, also, of course, no pleasure,

682
00:38:40.060 --> 00:38:45.780
but that isn't bad in itself or is the

683
00:38:45.780 --> 00:38:48.100
whole thing bad.

684
00:38:49.209 --> 00:38:51.639
This is what the debate with the epicurean rests

685
00:38:51.639 --> 00:38:54.790
on, and the epicurean does say, precisely because you

686
00:38:54.790 --> 00:38:57.800
will not experience anything after death, that it can't

687
00:38:57.800 --> 00:39:00.639
be bad. The suggestion is that because you aren't

688
00:39:00.639 --> 00:39:04.520
there when you die, when you're dead, it, it

689
00:39:04.520 --> 00:39:07.399
can't be bad for you. And the challenge of

690
00:39:07.399 --> 00:39:09.959
those wanting to respond to the epicurean is to

691
00:39:09.959 --> 00:39:12.959
provide an explanation for how it could possibly be

692
00:39:12.959 --> 00:39:16.360
bad for you if you no longer exist. And

693
00:39:16.360 --> 00:39:20.469
the most common form of that argument is what's

694
00:39:20.469 --> 00:39:23.909
called the deprivation account. What that says is that

695
00:39:23.909 --> 00:39:26.830
the antemortem person, that is to say, the person

696
00:39:26.830 --> 00:39:31.510
who existed before death, is deprived of the goods

697
00:39:31.510 --> 00:39:34.469
that he or she would have had if life

698
00:39:34.469 --> 00:39:38.510
had continued, uh, but is deprived of through, through

699
00:39:38.510 --> 00:39:41.729
death. And of course, a lot, much more needs

700
00:39:41.729 --> 00:39:43.820
to be said about the deprivation account. It needs

701
00:39:43.820 --> 00:39:46.780
to be qualified in various ways, but I think

702
00:39:46.780 --> 00:39:48.739
we can make sense of it. Now, we, we

703
00:39:48.739 --> 00:39:52.850
do need to acknowledge that Ceasing to exist and

704
00:39:52.850 --> 00:39:57.649
also coming into existence are very unusual kinds of

705
00:39:57.649 --> 00:39:59.929
cases. They're not the usual kind of cases. Normally,

706
00:39:59.969 --> 00:40:03.290
when something harms you, you exist in both of

707
00:40:03.290 --> 00:40:06.129
the possible scenarios, and then one of these scenarios

708
00:40:06.129 --> 00:40:08.669
is worse than the other one would have been.

709
00:40:09.689 --> 00:40:12.209
And the question is, how do you deal with

710
00:40:12.209 --> 00:40:16.159
these unusual cases? Do you Try to force them

711
00:40:16.159 --> 00:40:21.620
into. Your ordinary concepts, or do you recognize that

712
00:40:21.620 --> 00:40:24.459
because they're unusual kinds of cases, you need to

713
00:40:24.459 --> 00:40:28.760
adapt your concepts to the unusual case? And my

714
00:40:28.760 --> 00:40:30.939
view is that we should take that latter path.

715
00:40:31.399 --> 00:40:35.159
We should not presume that Uh, the unusual cases

716
00:40:35.159 --> 00:40:37.879
have to fit our usual concepts. If we need

717
00:40:37.879 --> 00:40:40.159
to alter our concepts in some way to account

718
00:40:40.159 --> 00:40:44.449
for unusual cases, then that's probably the wisest thing

719
00:40:44.449 --> 00:40:44.889
to do.

720
00:40:45.689 --> 00:40:51.129
Mhm, BUT if I understood something that you said

721
00:40:51.129 --> 00:40:57.389
earlier correctly, then there are at least a few

722
00:40:57.489 --> 00:41:04.969
situations where death is not as bad as going

723
00:41:04.969 --> 00:41:10.290
on living because of the kind of situation that

724
00:41:10.290 --> 00:41:14.729
people or a particular person finds themselves in.

725
00:41:16.050 --> 00:41:19.729
Correct. So, let's take that deprivation view. So, if

726
00:41:19.729 --> 00:41:23.199
the, the badness of your death depends on the

727
00:41:23.199 --> 00:41:25.600
extent to which you are deprived of future goods,

728
00:41:25.889 --> 00:41:28.860
we can well imagine people, because there are millions

729
00:41:28.860 --> 00:41:32.409
of such people whose quality of life has degenerated

730
00:41:32.409 --> 00:41:36.209
to the point that they cannot reasonably expect any

731
00:41:36.209 --> 00:41:38.909
future good. So their death doesn't deprive them of

732
00:41:38.909 --> 00:41:40.719
future good. All it does is deprive them of

733
00:41:40.719 --> 00:41:43.520
future bads. And so then you might say that

734
00:41:43.520 --> 00:41:45.840
death is the lesser of two evils for them.

735
00:41:47.020 --> 00:41:49.139
Uh, NOW, my own view about the badness of

736
00:41:49.139 --> 00:41:51.969
death is that it doesn't rest only on deprivation,

737
00:41:52.379 --> 00:41:55.260
uh, that another reason why death is bad is

738
00:41:55.260 --> 00:41:57.219
that it annihilates us. That is to say, it

739
00:41:57.219 --> 00:42:00.899
brings an irreversible end to our existence. And my

740
00:42:00.899 --> 00:42:02.649
own view is that that is a bad in

741
00:42:02.649 --> 00:42:05.860
itself, so that even when you are deprived of

742
00:42:05.860 --> 00:42:10.570
no goods by your death, You are still annihilated,

743
00:42:10.639 --> 00:42:14.260
and so it's still an evil, even if it's

744
00:42:14.350 --> 00:42:17.070
the lesser of two evils because continued existence would

745
00:42:17.070 --> 00:42:18.399
bring you so much pain and suffering.

746
00:42:20.010 --> 00:42:24.489
And do you think that immortality, if it would

747
00:42:24.489 --> 00:42:28.050
be possible, of course, uh, could be better?

